\title{Conducting Phishing Incident Response}

\taxon{skill}

\tag{phishing-response}

\tag{email-security}

\tag{credential-compromise}

\tag{email-header-analysis}

\tag{mailbox-remediation}

\meta{version}{1.0.0}

\meta{description}{Responds to phishing incidents by analyzing reported emails, extracting indicators, assessing credential compromise, quarantining malicious messages across the organization, and remediating affected accounts. Covers email header analysis, URL/attachment sandboxing, and mailbox-wide purge operations. Activates for requests involving phishing response, email incident, credential phishing, spear phishing investigation, or phishing remediation.}

\subtree{
\title{Conducting Phishing Incident Response}
\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\ul{
\li{A user reports receiving a suspicious email via the phishing report button or abuse mailbox}
\li{Email gateway detects a malicious email that bypassed initial filtering}
\li{Threat intelligence indicates an active phishing campaign targeting the organization}
\li{A user confirms they clicked a link or opened an attachment from a suspicious email}
\li{Credentials have been entered on a suspected phishing page}
}

\p{\strong{Do not use} for business email compromise (BEC) involving compromised internal accounts; use BEC response procedures which focus on account takeover investigation.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\ul{
\li{Email security gateway with message trace and quarantine capabilities (Microsoft Defender for Office 365, Proofpoint, Mimecast)}
\li{Microsoft 365 admin access or Google Workspace admin for mailbox search and purge}
\li{Malware sandbox for attachment and URL analysis (ANY.RUN, Joe Sandbox, Hybrid Analysis)}
\li{Email header analysis tools (MXToolbox Header Analyzer, Google Admin Toolbox)}
\li{Identity provider access for account remediation (Azure AD, Okta, Duo)}
\li{Phishing report intake process (dedicated mailbox or integrated report button)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\subtree{
\title{Step 1: Receive and Triage the Phishing Report}
\p{Evaluate the reported email to determine if it is malicious:}

\ul{
\li{Extract the email as an .EML or .MSG file (preserves headers)}
\li{Analyze email headers to determine the true sender, relay path, and authentication results}
}

\pre{\startverb
Email Header Analysis Checklist:
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
Return-Path:     billing@spoofed-domain[.]com
From:            "IT Support" <support@corp-lookalike[.]com>
Reply-To:        attacker@gmail[.]com (different from From)
SPF:             FAIL (sender IP not authorized for domain)
DKIM:            FAIL (signature invalid)
DMARC:           FAIL (policy: none - no enforcement)
Received:        from mail.attacker-infra[.]net [45.33.x.x]
X-Originating-IP: 45.33.x.x
Message-ID:      <random@attacker-infra.net>
\stopverb}

\p{Classification criteria:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Confirmed Phishing}: Malicious URL/attachment, spoofed sender, credential harvesting page}
\li{\strong{Suspicious}: Anomalous headers but no confirmed malicious content}
\li{\strong{Spam/Marketing}: Unwanted but not malicious}
\li{\strong{Legitimate}: Not a phishing email (false report)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 2: Analyze Malicious Content}
\p{Examine URLs and attachments in a safe environment:}

\p{\strong{URL Analysis:}}

\ul{
\li{Check URL against VirusTotal, URLscan.io, and Google Safe Browsing}
\li{Open URL in a sandbox browser to capture the landing page}
\li{Check if the URL redirects to a credential harvesting page}
\li{Identify the phishing kit type (Microsoft 365 login clone, Okta clone, generic)}
\li{Determine if the phishing page is still active}
}

\p{\strong{Attachment Analysis:}}

\ul{
\li{Calculate file hash (SHA-256) and check against VirusTotal}
\li{Detonate in sandbox (ANY.RUN, Joe Sandbox)}
\li{Analyze document for macros (olevba for Office files)}
\li{Check for embedded exploits (CVE exploitation in document parsers)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 3: Determine Scope of Impact}
\p{Identify all recipients and assess who interacted with the phishing email:}

\pre{\startverb
Scope Assessment:
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
Total Recipients:     47 users
Delivered to Inbox:   38 users (9 caught by email gateway)
Opened Email:         24 users (email tracking pixel data)
Clicked Link:         8 users (proxy/firewall logs)
Entered Credentials:  3 users (phishing page submitted form data)
Opened Attachment:    2 users (EDR process execution telemetry)
\stopverb}

\p{Search methods:}

\ul{
\li{Microsoft 365: Use Threat Explorer or Content Search to find all instances of the email}
\li{Google Workspace: Use Admin Console > Investigation tool for message search}
\li{Proxy logs: Search for connections to the phishing URL from internal IPs}
\li{EDR: Search for attachment file hash execution across all endpoints}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 4: Contain the Threat}
\p{Execute containment actions based on impact assessment:}

\p{\strong{Email Containment:}}

\ul{
\li{Purge the phishing email from all mailboxes using Microsoft 365 Content Search and Purge or Google Workspace Admin delete}
\li{Block the sender domain at the email gateway}
\li{Add the phishing URL to the web proxy blocklist}
\li{Add attachment hash to email gateway and EDR blocklists}
}

\p{\strong{Account Containment (for users who entered credentials):}}

\ul{
\li{Force password reset immediately}
\li{Revoke all active sessions and OAuth tokens}
\li{Enable or re-verify MFA enrollment}
\li{Review mailbox rules for attacker-created forwarding rules}
\li{Check for unauthorized OAuth application grants}
\li{Review recent sign-in activity for suspicious locations}
}

\pre{\startverb
# Microsoft 365: Revoke sessions and reset password
Connect-AzureAD
Revoke-AzureADUserAllRefreshToken -ObjectId "user@corp.com"
Set-AzureADUserPassword -ObjectId "user@corp.com" -ForceChangePasswordNextLogin $true

# Check for mailbox forwarding rules
Get-InboxRule -Mailbox "user@corp.com" | Where-Object {$_.ForwardTo -or $_.RedirectTo}

# Remove suspicious forwarding rules
Remove-InboxRule -Mailbox "user@corp.com" -Identity "Rule Name"
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 5: Eradicate and Recover}
\p{Remove all traces of the phishing attack:}

\ul{
\li{Confirm email purge completed successfully across all mailboxes}
\li{Verify compromised accounts have been secured (password changed, sessions revoked, MFA verified)}
\li{Remove any malware installed via phishing attachments from affected endpoints}
\li{Monitor compromised accounts for 72 hours for signs of continued unauthorized access}
\li{Check for data exfiltration from compromised accounts during the exposure window}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 6: Post-Incident Actions}
\p{Strengthen defenses against similar phishing attacks:}

\ul{
\li{Report the phishing URL to Google Safe Browsing and Microsoft SmartScreen}
\li{Submit the phishing domain for takedown via the domain registrar abuse contact}
\li{Update email gateway filtering rules based on observed evasion techniques}
\li{Send targeted security awareness notification to affected users}
\li{Update phishing simulation program to include the observed technique}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Key Concepts}
\pre{\startverb
| Term | Definition |
|------|------------|
| **Spear Phishing** | Targeted phishing attack crafted for a specific individual or organization using personalized content |
| **Credential Harvesting** | Phishing technique that mimics a legitimate login page to capture usernames and passwords |
| **SPF (Sender Policy Framework)** | Email authentication protocol that specifies which mail servers are authorized to send email for a domain |
| **DKIM (DomainKeys Identified Mail)** | Email authentication method using cryptographic signatures to verify that an email was not altered in transit |
| **DMARC** | Policy framework that uses SPF and DKIM to determine email authenticity and instructs receivers on handling failures |
| **OAuth Consent Phishing** | Attack that tricks users into granting malicious OAuth applications access to their email and data |
| **Email Header** | Metadata embedded in every email containing routing, authentication, and sender information used for forensic analysis |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Tools & Systems}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Microsoft Defender for Office 365}: Email threat protection with Threat Explorer for investigation and automated purge}
\li{\strong{Proofpoint TAP (Targeted Attack Protection)}: Email security platform with URL rewriting and attachment sandboxing}
\li{\strong{URLscan.io}: Online service that scans URLs and captures screenshots of phishing pages for evidence}
\li{\strong{PhishTool}: Phishing analysis platform that automates header analysis, URL inspection, and IOC extraction}
\li{\strong{GoPhish}: Open-source phishing simulation platform for security awareness testing}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Scenarios}
\subtree{
\title{Scenario: Microsoft 365 Credential Phishing via QR Code}
\p{\strong{Context}: Users report an email claiming to be from IT requiring MFA re-enrollment. The email contains a QR code that links to a convincing Microsoft 365 login page clone hosted on a compromised WordPress site.}

\p{\strong{Approach}:}

\ol{
\li{Scan the QR code in a sandbox to extract the URL}
\li{Analyze the phishing page: captures credentials and MFA tokens (adversary-in-the-middle attack)}
\li{Search email gateway for all recipients using message subject and sender as search criteria}
\li{Cross-reference with proxy logs to identify users who visited the phishing URL}
\li{Force password reset and revoke sessions for all users who visited the URL}
\li{Purge the email from all mailboxes and block the sender domain}
\li{Notify users about the specific campaign with visual examples of the phishing email}
}

\p{\strong{Pitfalls}:}

\ul{
\li{Not checking for adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) capability that captures session tokens even with MFA}
\li{Only resetting passwords without revoking active sessions (attacker retains access via stolen session cookies)}
\li{Not searching for mailbox forwarding rules created by the attacker after compromising an account}
\li{Missing QR code phishing (quishing) because URL scanning tools cannot decode QR code images}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Output Format}
\pre{\startverb
PHISHING INCIDENT RESPONSE REPORT
===================================
Incident:          INC-2025-1602
Date Reported:     2025-11-16T09:15:00Z
Reported By:       jdoe@corp.example.com
Classification:    Credential Phishing (AiTM)

EMAIL ANALYSIS
Subject:       "Action Required: MFA Re-enrollment"
Sender:        it-support@corp-security[.]com (spoofed)
SPF:           FAIL | DKIM: FAIL | DMARC: FAIL
Phishing URL:  hxxps://compromised-site[.]com/ms365/login
Phishing Type: Microsoft 365 AiTM credential harvester

IMPACT ASSESSMENT
Recipients:        47
Clicked Link:      8
Credentials Entered: 3 (confirmed via proxy POST data)

CONTAINMENT ACTIONS
[x] Email purged from all 47 mailboxes
[x] Phishing domain blocked at web proxy
[x] Sender domain blocked at email gateway
[x] 3 compromised accounts: passwords reset, sessions revoked
[x] Mailbox forwarding rules reviewed (1 malicious rule removed)
[x] OAuth app grants reviewed (no unauthorized grants found)

IOCs EXTRACTED
Domain:  corp-security[.]com
URL:     hxxps://compromised-site[.]com/ms365/login
IP:      104.21.x.x (Cloudflare-hosted)
Sender:  it-support@corp-security[.]com

RECOMMENDATIONS
1. Implement DMARC enforcement (p=reject) for corp domain
2. Deploy QR code scanning in email gateway
3. Send targeted awareness notification to all 47 recipients
4. Request domain takedown via registrar abuse contact
\stopverb}
}
}